######_Most useful block elements (and why)

.div — generic container for grouping and layout (use with classes).

*p — paragraph, for blocks of text.

*h1…h6 — headings, for document structure and SEO.

*section — thematic grouping of content (semantic).

*article — self-contained content (blog post, news item).

*nav — navigation links container.

*header, footer — page/section header and footer.

*aside — sidebar or tangential content.

*form — grouping interactive controls and submission.

*ul / ol / li — lists.

*table, thead, tbody, tr, td — tabular data.

When to use: structure pages, group components, layout blocks and semantic sections.

######_Most useful inline elements (and why)

*a — links (essential).

*span — generic inline wrapper (useful for styling a few words).

*img — images (inline by default, but behaves like replaced element).

*strong, b — important/strong text (use strong for semantics).

*em, i — emphasis (use em for semantics).

*label — label for form controls (improves accessibility).

*input, button, select, textarea — form controls (inline by default).

*small, sup, sub — fine typographic bits.

*code, kbd, samp — inline code and keyboard text.
Quick reference (cheat-sheet)
<!-- summary -->
Use block: div, p, h1-h6, section, article, nav, header, footer, form, ul/ol/li


Use inline: a, span, img, strong/em, label, input, button, code
